<p class="body">Panama Geisha — specifically from the Boquete highlands where Hacienda La Esmeralda established the benchmark — expresses jasmine, tropical fruit, and a bergamot-like complexity at its peak. The best lots have a clarity and aromatic lift that experienced cuppers call transcendent. Those lots also command prices that make them inaccessible to most roasters as a regular menu offering.</p>

<p class="body">Nicaragua Geisha from well-situated farms like El Quetzal produces a different expression of the same varietal. The Matagalpa micro-climate — cool nights, volcanic soil, consistent rainfall, shade-grown under established canopies — produces a cup with strong jasmine aromatics, stone fruit notes of peach and apple, and the tea-like clarity that defines good Geisha. It's not an imitation of Panama; it's Nicaragua's version, shaped by its own terroir.</p>

<div class="callout">
  <p>The honest comparison for roasters: Nicaragua Geisha won't replace Panama auction lots in terms of prestige or competition placement. What it offers is genuine Geisha character — the florals, the clarity, the delicacy — at a price point that allows building a real program rather than a single show lot.</p>
</div>

<h2 class="section-head">El Quetzal's <em>Geisha: The Details</em></h2>

<p class="body">El Quetzal began harvesting Geisha at Finca El Quetzal in Matagalpa in 2024. The 2026 harvest cupped at 87 points — strong for a second-year Geisha program. The farm's Geisha grows under the same shade canopies and volcanic soil conditions as the flagship Java lots, benefiting from the farm's established cultivation infrastructure and the fourth-generation expertise of the Bendaña McEwan family.</p>

<p class="body">The washed processing method — which most Geisha producers favor for expressing the varietal's aromatic complexity — is handled at the farm's own mill (Beneficio San Miguel), maintaining full traceability from tree to export without importer intermediaries.</p>

<p class="body">Current cupping profile: jasmine, peach, apple, with a tea-like quality at finish. SCA Specialty Grade, 98.6% exportable, screen 77.9% above #18.</p>

<h2 class="section-head">How to <em>Roast Geisha</em></h2>

<p class="body">Geisha is nearly universally roasted light. The florals and fruit notes that define the varietal are heat-sensitive — they exist in the early stages of roast development and diminish rapidly as the roast progresses. The goal is to develop sweetness and body while preserving aromatic complexity.</p>

<p class="body">Practically: aim for City to City+ on your roaster's development curve. The first crack arrival and post-crack development time will depend on your specific drum or fluid bed setup, but the principle is consistent: develop enough to produce sweetness, stop well before the onset of second crack. A 20-22% development ratio works well as a starting point for most drum roasters.</p>

<p class="body">Grind and brew: pour-over formats (V60, Chemex, Kalita) suit Geisha better than espresso for most applications. The lighter body and aromatic complexity express more clearly through a clean filter brew than under pressure. If running Geisha as espresso, use a lower dose and shorter extraction time than your standard blend — 16-17g in, 32-34g out, 25-28 seconds — to preserve brightness.</p>

<h2 class="section-head">Sourcing <em>Nicaragua Geisha Green Coffee</em></h2>

<p class="body">El Quetzal offers farm-direct Nicaragua Geisha green coffee at <a href="https://elquetzal.coffee/collections/geisha" style="color: var(--gold); text-decoration: none;">elquetzal.coffee</a>. Sample packs allow evaluation before committing to a full lot. The 2024/25 harvest is currently available; 2025/26 lots are in progress.</p>

<p class="body">Production is genuinely limited — Geisha is a young program at the farm, and the early harvests are small by design. Roasters who want allocation for upcoming harvests should reach out directly to El Quetzal to discuss forward contract options.</p>

